Emperors

Emperors

In total, 24 Chinese emperors occupied the Forbidden City, so named because it could only be accessed by the emperor, his immediate family, his women and thousands of eunuchs. Find out what they have to say.

Emperors Alt

Emperors

IIn total, 24 Chinese emperors occupied the Forbidden City, so named because it could only be accessed by the emperor, his immediate family, his women and thousands of eunuchs. Find out what they have to say.

Forbiddencity

Forbidden City

At the beginning of the fifteenth century AD, the third Ming Emperor, Yung-lo created one of the most dazzling architectural masterpieces in the world. Forbidden City, the Imperial Palace complex in Beijing served as the home for emerors for hundreds of years.

Learn more about the palace.

Travel Tips

Before starting your visit, it is quite helpful for you to grab some basic travel tips for visiting The Forbidden City.

Read more

Emperors

In total, 24 Chinese emperors occupied the Forbidden City, so named because it could only be accessed by the emperor, his immediate family, his women and thousands of eunuchs. Find out what they have to say.

Emperors

In total, 24 Chinese emperors occupied the Forbidden City, so named because it could only be accessed by the emperor, his immediate family, his women and thousands of eunuchs. Find out what they have to say.

Learn more about the emperors

What To See

Embark on a unique journey through a palace once forbidden to the general public and glimpse into the world of the Ming (1368–1644) and Qing (1644 – 1911) dynasties.

What To See

Embark on a unique journey through a palace once forbidden to the general public and glimpse into the world of the Ming (1368–1644) and Qing (1644 – 1911) dynasties.

Plan your visit

Travel Tips

Before starting your visit, it is quite helpful for you to grab some basic travel tips for visiting The Forbidden City.

History

Today, there are still many stories waiting to be told about the Forbidden City.

Learn more about the palace.

Emperors

In total, 24 Chinese emperors occupied the Forbidden City, so named because it could only be accessed by the emperor, his immediate family, his women and thousands of eunuchs. Find out what they have to say.

Learn more about the emperors

What To See

Embark on a unique journey through a palace once forbidden to the general public and glimpse into the world of the Ming (1368–1644) and Qing (1644 – 1911) dynasties.

Plan your visit

Emperors

In total, 24 Chinese emperors occupied the Forbidden City, so named because it could only be accessed by the emperor, his immediate family, his women and thousands of eunuchs. Find out what they have to say.

Learn more about the emperors

Whattosee

What To See

Embark on a unique journey through a palace once forbidden to the general public and glimpse into the world of the Ming (1368–1644) and Qing (1644 – 1911) dynasties.

Whattosee Alt

What To See

Embark on a unique journey through a palace once forbidden to the general public and glimpse into the world of the Ming (1368–1644) and Qing (1644 – 1911) dynasties.
